Abu Dhabi Shares Rise Most in Three Weeks on Aldar Earnings Bets

-- B y   Z a h r a a   A l k h a l i s i
-- 
2011-07-26T13:05:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-26/abu-dhabi-shares-rise-most-in-three-weeks-on-aldar-earnings-bets.html
Abu Dhabi ’s benchmark index climbed
the most in three weeks, leading gains in Persian Gulf markets,
on speculation  Aldar Properties PJSC (ALDAR) ’s earnings will beat
analsyts’ estimates.  Aldar, the emirate’s biggest developer, advanced the most
since July 3. Sorouh Real Estate PJSC, Abu Dhabi’s second-
largest, increased the most in more than three months. Abu
Dhabi’s  ADX General Index (ADSMI)  advanced 0.4 percent, the most since
July 5, to 2,673.97 at the 2 p.m. close in the emirate. Dubai’s
 DFM General Index (DFMGI)  snapped a three-day decline, gaining less than
0.1 percent. About 57 million shares traded in Abu Dhabi today
compared with a six-month daily average of 76 million shares.  “Investors are expecting positive numbers for Aldar, which
pushed most real-estate names higher,” said Sherif El Zeneiny,
head of equity trading at National Bank of Abu Dhabi PJSC.
“Volumes have been declining, which is expected due to summer
holiday.”  The ADX Real-Estate Index jumped 2.6 percent. Aldar rose
2.4 percent to 1.28 dirhams. Sorouh advanced 3.3 percent, the
most since April 19, to 1.25 dirhams. Aldar may say July 28
second-quarter profit was 157.5 million dirhams ($43 million)
after a loss in the year-earlier period, according to the median
estimate of four analysts on Bloomberg. Sorouh’s profit for the
period may soar fivefold to 155.5 million dirhams, according to
six analyst estimates on Bloomberg.  Shuaa Gains  Emaar Properties PJSC (EMAAR) , the developer of the world’s tallest
tower in Dubai, said after the market closed second-quarter
profit was 250 million dirhams, beating the 233 million-dirham
median estimate of seven analysts on Bloomberg. The shares
retreated 0.4 percent to 2.88 dirhams.  Dubai-based  Shuaa Capital PSC (SHUAA)  surged 5.1 percent, the most
in a week, to 99.8 fils. The investment bank controlled by
Dubai’s ruler returned to profit, ending two consecutive
quarterly losses amid political unrest in the  Middle East .  Kuwait’s SE Price Index increased 0.4 percent, Oman’s  MSM30
Index (MSM30)  added 0.1 percent, while Bahrain’s measure and Qatar’s
gauge rose less than 0.1 percent.  Saudi Arabia ’s Tadawul All
Share Index gained less than 0.1 percent and the  Bloomberg GCC
200 Index (BGCC200)  advanced 0.1 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
